---
import BaseLayout from '../../layouts/BaseLayout.astro';
const title = 'How Wage Theft Claims Work | wagetheftcalc.com';
const description = 'Step-by-step guide to filing a wage theft claim with the DOL or through a private lawsuit.';
---
<BaseLayout title={title} description={description}>
  <h1>How Wage Theft Claims Work</h1>
  <h2>Option 1: DOL Wage and Hour Division</h2>
  <p>File a free complaint with the U.S. Department of Labor's Wage and Hour Division at dol.gov/agencies/whd. WHD investigates and, if violations are found, can recover up to 2 years of back wages plus equal liquidated damages. WHD represents all affected employees — you don't need an attorney.</p>
  <h2>Option 2: Private Lawsuit</h2>
  <p>File suit in federal or state court. Recoverable damages include: back wages, liquidated damages, attorney fees, and costs. FLSA collective actions allow similarly situated coworkers to join. Most employment attorneys handle these on contingency.</p>
  <h2>Option 3: State Agency</h2>
  <p>Most states have labor commissioner offices that handle wage claims, often with faster resolution and longer lookback periods than the FLSA. State law may provide greater damages.</p>
  <h2>Evidence to Gather</h2>
  <ul>
    <li>Pay stubs and direct deposit records</li>
    <li>Time records (personal notes, phone records, texts, emails)</li>
    <li>Employment contract or offer letter</li>
    <li>Handbooks or written policies</li>
    <li>Witness statements from coworkers</li>
  </ul>
  <h2>Statute of Limitations</h2>
  <p>Act quickly. FLSA: 2 years (3 if willful). State laws: often 3–6 years. The clock runs from each missed paycheck, not your last day of work.</p>
</BaseLayout>
